Acting National Police Commissioner Kgomotso Phahlane has on Thursday assured that police will exercise &#8220;maximum restraint&#8221; during proceedings related to the State of The Nation Address(SONA).&#8220;Nothing that we do must be outside the framework of the law. Throughout we will exercise maximum restraint and that is very important,&#8221; said Phahlane.&#8220;Let us not disappoint the people of this country by doing anything contrary of what is expected of us,&#8221; continued Phahlane.The Acting Police Commissioner was addressing police officers deployed to ensure security during proceedings related to the SONA.#SONA2017 Acting National Commissioner Phahlane is about to address #SAPS security personnel. @ANN7tv pic.twitter.com/qpTUhNkLJN Kalden O Lachungpa (@KaldenOngmu) February 9, 2017&#8220;Our plan must be executed without fear or favour and we need to ensure that our people feel safe as the President is set to deliver SONA &#8221; said Phahlane.Phahlane also brushed off concerns which have been raised following a decision by President Jacob Zuma to deploy 441 members of the South African National Defence Force (SANDF) to the SONA in order to maintain &#8220;law and order.&#8221;&#8220;The deployment of the national defense force is nothing foreign, they are here for support,&#8221; said Phahlane.Opposition parties have criticised the decision saying it was the beginning of an authoritarian state with the DA Chief Whip John Steenhuisen saying Zuma was &#8220;paranoid&#8221;. #SONA2017 security. Haven&#8217;t spotted a single SANDF soldiers around the parliament premises. @ANN7tv pic.twitter.com/NuKzC5btBJ Kalden O Lachungpa (@KaldenOngmu) February 9, 2017 However government representatives have consistently stated that the soldiers would be on stand-by and will not be on the parliamentary premises.Meanwhile Phahlane told police to expect provocation but they should remain calm at all times.&#8220;Each and every one of you has a role to play. You will not run away from your responsibility. We will be incited. But we will not allow lawlessness. We will police without fear of favour,&#8221; said Phahlane.-TNA Reporter